
[1]peremptory

   PER'EMPTORY, a. [L. peremptorius, from peremptus, taken away, killed.]

   1. Express; positive; absolute; decisive; authoritative; in a manner to
   preclude debate or expostulation. The orders of the commander are
   peremptory.

   2. Positive in opinion or judgment. The genuine effect of sound
   learning is to make men less peremptory in their determinations.

   3. Final; determinate.

   4. Peremptory challenge, in law, a challenge or right of challenging
   jurors without showing cause.
